The perimeter of $\triangle PQS$ is the sum of the lengths of the sides of the triangle. 

First, we need to find the length of side $PQ$. We can use the Pythagorean theorem to find the length of side $PQ$ as follows:

$$
\begin{align*}
PQ &= \sqrt{(Q_x - P_x)^2 + (Q_y - P_y)^2} \\
&= \sqrt{(0 - 12)^2 + (0 - 0)^2} \\
&= \sqrt{12^2 + 0^2} \\
&= \sqrt{144} \\
&= 12\sqrt{2}
\end{align*}
$$

Next, we need to find the length of side $QS$. We can use the Pythagorean theorem to find the length of side $QS$ as follows:

$$
\begin{align*}
QS &= \sqrt{(S_x - Q_x)^2 + (S_y - Q_y)^2} \\
&= \sqrt{(0 - 0)^2 + (-20 - 0)^2} \\
&= \sqrt{0^2 + 400} \\
&= 20\sqrt{2}
\end{align*}
$$

Finally, we need to find the length of side $PR$. We can use the Pythagorean theorem to find the length of side $PR$ as follows:

$$
\begin{align*}
PR &= \sqrt{(R_x - P_x)^2 + (R_y - P_y)^2} \\
&= \sqrt{(0 - 12)^2 + (-5 - 0)^2} \\
&= \sqrt{12^2 + 25} \\
&= \sqrt{169} \\
&= 13\sqrt{2}
\end{align*}
$$

Therefore, the perimeter of $\triangle PQS$ is:

$$
\begin{align*}
\text{perimeter} &= PQ + QS + PR \\
&= 12\sqrt{2} + 20\sqrt{2} + 13\sqrt{2} \\
&= 53\sqrt{2}
\end{align*}
$$

