**Rotation Transformation**

To rotate a point $P$ around the origin by an angle $\theta$ clockwise, we can use the following formula:

$$
\begin{bmatrix}
x' \\
y'
\end{bmatrix} = 
\begin{bmatrix}
\cos \theta & -\sin \theta \\
\sin \theta & \cos \theta
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
x \\
y
\end{bmatrix}
$$

In this case, we want to rotate the point $(-3,2)$ by $90^{\circ}$ clockwise around the origin. We can use the following trigonometric identities to find the rotation matrix:

$$
\begin{bmatrix}
\cos \theta & -\sin \theta \\
\sin \theta & \cos \theta
\end{bmatrix} = 
\begin{bmatrix}
\cos \theta & \sin \theta \\
-\sin \theta & \cos \theta
\end{bmatrix}
