To reflect a point $P$ across a line $L$, we can use the following formula:

$$
\begin{bmatrix}
x' \\
y'
\end{bmatrix} = 
\begin{bmatrix}
1 & 0 \\
0 & -1
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
x \\
y
\end{bmatrix}
$$

In this case, we want to reflect the point $B$ across the line $y=x$. We can use the following formula for the slope of the line:

$$
m = \frac{y_2 - y_1}{x_2 - x_1} = \frac{2 - (-3)}{2} = -1
$$

Therefore, the equation of the line is $y = -x$. We can use this to find the point of intersection between the line and the x-axis:

$$
\begin{bmatrix}
0 \\
-x
\end{bmatrix} = 
\begin{bmatrix}
1 & 0 \\
0 & -1
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
-3 \\
2
\end{bmatrix}
$$

$$
